// COMPILE_FAIL: == on multi-field custom struct without PartialEq (typeck guard, S105)
//
// Before S104-B, equality on a multi-field aggregate fell through to
// emit_binop_typed's extract-first-field branch, which silently
// extracted only the first field and compared it. For `Point { x, y }`
// that meant `Point { x: 1, y: 2 } == Point { x: 1, y: 99 }` returned
// `true` because only `x` was inspected — a silent miscompile.
//
// S104-B caught this at codegen time with a fatal E0806. S105 promotes
// the guard to typeck time as a `T: PartialEq` requirement on the operand
// of `==` / `!=`. The codegen-level guard remains as defense in depth.
//
// Workarounds:
//   - custom struct: `#[derive(PartialEq)]` and the operator dispatches
//     to the synthesized `eq` method.
//   - Option/Result/Vec: implicitly PartialEq when their type args are.
//   - HashMap: not supported (architectural; needs iteration).
//   - closure: not comparable.
//
// EXPECT: does not implement `PartialEq`
mod std;

struct Point {
    x: i32,
    y: i32,
}

fn main() -> i32 {
    let p1 = Point { x: 1, y: 2 };
    let p2 = Point { x: 1, y: 99 };
    if p1 == p2 { 0 } else { 1 }
}
